  54 @pytest.fixture
  55 def filepath_or_buffer(filepath_or_buffer_id, tmp_path):
  56     """
  57     A fixture yielding a string representing a filepath, a path-like object
  58     and a StringIO buffer. Also checks that buffer is not closed.
  59     """
  60     if filepath_or_buffer_id == "buffer":
  61         buf = StringIO()
  62         yield buf
  63         assert not buf.closed
  64     else:
  65         assert isinstance(tmp_path, Path)
  66         if filepath_or_buffer_id == "pathlike":
  67             yield tmp_path / "foo"
  68         else:
  69             yield str(tmp_path / "foo")

  72 @pytest.fixture
  73 def assert_filepath_or_buffer_equals(
  74     filepath_or_buffer, filepath_or_buffer_id, encoding
  75 ):
  76     """
  77     Assertion helper for checking filepath_or_buffer.
  78     """
  79 
  80     def _assert_filepath_or_buffer_equals(expected):
  81         if filepath_or_buffer_id == "string":
  82             with open(filepath_or_buffer, encoding=encoding) as f:
  83                 result = f.read()
  84         elif filepath_or_buffer_id == "pathlike":
  85             result = filepath_or_buffer.read_text(encoding=encoding)
  86         elif filepath_or_buffer_id == "buffer":
  87             result = filepath_or_buffer.getvalue()
  88         assert result == expected
  89 
  90     return _assert_filepath_or_buffer_equals

  98 def has_info_repr(df):
  99     r = repr(df)
 100     c1 = r.split("\n")[0].startswith("<class")
 101     c2 = r.split("\n")[0].startswith(r"&lt;class")  # _repr_html_
 102     return c1 or c2
 103 
 104 
 105 def has_non_verbose_info_repr(df):
 106     has_info = has_info_repr(df)
 107     r = repr(df)
 108 
 109     # 1. <class>
 110     # 2. Index
 111     # 3. Columns
 112     # 4. dtype
 113     # 5. memory usage
 114     # 6. trailing newline
 115     nv = len(r.split("\n")) == 6
 116     return has_info and nv
 117 
 118 
 119 def has_horizontally_truncated_repr(df):
 120     try:  # Check header row
 121         fst_line = np.array(repr(df).splitlines()[0].split())
 122         cand_col = np.where(fst_line == "...")[0][0]
 123     except IndexError:
 124         return False
 125     # Make sure each row has this ... in the same place
 126     r = repr(df)
 127     for ix, l in enumerate(r.splitlines()):
 128         if not r.split()[cand_col] == "...":
 129             return False
 130     return True
 131 
 132 
 133 def has_vertically_truncated_repr(df):
 134     r = repr(df)
 135     only_dot_row = False
 136     for row in r.splitlines():
 137         if re.match(r"^[\.\ ]+$", row):
 138             only_dot_row = True
 139     return only_dot_row
 140 
 141 
 142 def has_truncated_repr(df):
 143     return has_horizontally_truncated_repr(df) or has_vertically_truncated_repr(df)
 144 
 145 
 146 def has_doubly_truncated_repr(df):
 147     return has_horizontally_truncated_repr(df) and has_vertically_truncated_repr(df)
 148 
 149 
 150 def has_expanded_repr(df):
 151     r = repr(df)
 152     for line in r.split("\n"):
 153         if line.endswith("\\"):
 154             return True
 155     return False

 184     def test_show_null_counts(self):
 185 
 186         df = DataFrame(1, columns=range(10), index=range(10))
 187         df.iloc[1, 1] = np.nan
 188 
 189         def check(null_counts, result):
 190             buf = StringIO()
 191             df.info(buf=buf, null_counts=null_counts)
 192             assert ("non-null" in buf.getvalue()) is result
 193 
 194         with option_context(
 195             "display.max_info_rows", 20, "display.max_info_columns", 20
 196         ):
 197             check(None, True)
 198             check(True, True)
 199             check(False, False)
 200 
 201         with option_context("display.max_info_rows", 5, "display.max_info_columns", 5):
 202             check(None, False)
 203             check(True, False)
 204             check(False, False)

 213     def test_repr_truncation(self):
 214         max_len = 20
 215         with option_context("display.max_colwidth", max_len):
 216             df = DataFrame(
 217                 {
 218                     "A": np.random.randn(10),
 219                     "B": [
 220                         tm.rands(np.random.randint(max_len - 1, max_len + 1))
 221                         for i in range(10)
 222                     ],
 223                 }
 224             )
 225             r = repr(df)
 226             r = r[r.find("\n") + 1 :]
 227 
 228             adj = fmt._get_adjustment()
 229 
 230             for line, value in zip(r.split("\n"), df["B"]):
 231                 if adj.len(value) + 1 > max_len:
 232                     assert "..." in line
 233                 else:
 234                     assert "..." not in line
 235 
 236         with option_context("display.max_colwidth", 999999):
 237             assert "..." not in repr(df)
 238 
 239         with option_context("display.max_colwidth", max_len + 2):
 240             assert "..." not in repr(df)

 314     def test_repr_should_return_str(self):
 315         # https://docs.python.org/3/reference/datamodel.html#object.__repr__
 316         # "...The return value must be a string object."
 317 
 318         # (str on py2.x, str (unicode) on py3)
 319 
 320         data = [8, 5, 3, 5]
 321         index1 = ["\u03c3", "\u03c4", "\u03c5", "\u03c6"]
 322         cols = ["\u03c8"]
 323         df = DataFrame(data, columns=cols, index=index1)
 324         assert type(df.__repr__()) == str  # both py2 / 3

 331     def test_expand_frame_repr(self):
 332         df_small = DataFrame("hello", index=[0], columns=[0])
 333         df_wide = DataFrame("hello", index=[0], columns=range(10))
 334         df_tall = DataFrame("hello", index=range(30), columns=range(5))
 335 
 336         with option_context("mode.sim_interactive", True):
 337             with option_context(
 338                 "display.max_columns",
 339                 10,
 340                 "display.width",
 341                 20,
 342                 "display.max_rows",
 343                 20,
 344                 "display.show_dimensions",
 345                 True,
 346             ):
 347                 with option_context("display.expand_frame_repr", True):
 348                     assert not has_truncated_repr(df_small)
 349                     assert not has_expanded_repr(df_small)
 350                     assert not has_truncated_repr(df_wide)
 351                     assert has_expanded_repr(df_wide)
 352                     assert has_vertically_truncated_repr(df_tall)
 353                     assert has_expanded_repr(df_tall)
 354 
 355                 with option_context("display.expand_frame_repr", False):
 356                     assert not has_truncated_repr(df_small)
 357                     assert not has_expanded_repr(df_small)
 358                     assert not has_horizontally_truncated_repr(df_wide)
 359                     assert not has_expanded_repr(df_wide)
 360                     assert has_vertically_truncated_repr(df_tall)
 361                     assert not has_expanded_repr(df_tall)

 374     def test_repr_truncates_terminal_size(self, monkeypatch):
 375         # see gh-21180
 376 
 377         terminal_size = (118, 96)
 378         monkeypatch.setattr(
 379             "pandas.io.formats.format.get_terminal_size", lambda: terminal_size
 380         )
 381 
 382         index = range(5)
 383         columns = pd.MultiIndex.from_tuples(
 384             [
 385                 ("This is a long title with > 37 chars.", "cat"),
 386                 ("This is a loooooonger title with > 43 chars.", "dog"),
 387             ]
 388         )
 389         df = pd.DataFrame(1, index=index, columns=columns)
 390 
 391         result = repr(df)
 392 
 393         h1, h2 = result.split("\n")[:2]
 394         assert "long" in h1
 395         assert "loooooonger" in h1
 396         assert "cat" in h2
 397         assert "dog" in h2
 398 
 399         # regular columns
 400         df2 = pd.DataFrame({"A" * 41: [1, 2], "B" * 41: [1, 2]})
 401         result = repr(df2)
 402 
 403         assert df2.columns[0] in result.split("\n")[0]

 430     def test_repr_max_columns_max_rows(self):
 431         term_width, term_height = get_terminal_size()
 432         if term_width < 10 or term_height < 10:
 433             pytest.skip(f"terminal size too small, {term_width} x {term_height}")
 434 
 435         def mkframe(n):
 436             index = [f"{i:05d}" for i in range(n)]
 437             return DataFrame(0, index, index)
 438 
 439         df6 = mkframe(6)
 440         df10 = mkframe(10)
 441         with option_context("mode.sim_interactive", True):
 442             with option_context("display.width", term_width * 2):
 443                 with option_context("display.max_rows", 5, "display.max_columns", 5):
 444                     assert not has_expanded_repr(mkframe(4))
 445                     assert not has_expanded_repr(mkframe(5))
 446                     assert not has_expanded_repr(df6)
 447                     assert has_doubly_truncated_repr(df6)
 448 
 449                 with option_context("display.max_rows", 20, "display.max_columns", 10):
 450                     # Out off max_columns boundary, but no extending
 451                     # since not exceeding width
 452                     assert not has_expanded_repr(df6)
 453                     assert not has_truncated_repr(df6)
 454 
 455                 with option_context("display.max_rows", 9, "display.max_columns", 10):
 456                     # out vertical bounds can not result in expanded repr
 457                     assert not has_expanded_repr(df10)
 458                     assert has_vertically_truncated_repr(df10)
 459 
 460             # width=None in terminal, auto detection
 461             with option_context(
 462                 "display.max_columns",
 463                 100,
 464                 "display.max_rows",
 465                 term_width * 20,
 466                 "display.width",
 467                 None,
 468             ):
 469                 df = mkframe((term_width // 7) - 2)
 470                 assert not has_expanded_repr(df)
 471                 df = mkframe((term_width // 7) + 2)
 472                 printing.pprint_thing(df._repr_fits_horizontal_())
 473                 assert has_expanded_repr(df)

 475     def test_repr_min_rows(self):
 476         df = pd.DataFrame({"a": range(20)})
 477 
 478         # default setting no truncation even if above min_rows
 479         assert ".." not in repr(df)
 480         assert ".." not in df._repr_html_()
 481 
 482         df = pd.DataFrame({"a": range(61)})
 483 
 484         # default of max_rows 60 triggers truncation if above
 485         assert ".." in repr(df)
 486         assert ".." in df._repr_html_()
 487 
 488         with option_context("display.max_rows", 10, "display.min_rows", 4):
 489             # truncated after first two rows
 490             assert ".." in repr(df)
 491             assert "2  " not in repr(df)
 492             assert "..." in df._repr_html_()
 493             assert "<td>2</td>" not in df._repr_html_()
 494 
 495         with option_context("display.max_rows", 12, "display.min_rows", None):
 496             # when set to None, follow value of max_rows
 497             assert "5    5" in repr(df)
 498             assert "<td>5</td>" in df._repr_html_()
 499 
 500         with option_context("display.max_rows", 10, "display.min_rows", 12):
 501             # when set value higher as max_rows, use the minimum
 502             assert "5    5" not in repr(df)
 503             assert "<td>5</td>" not in df._repr_html_()
 504 
 505         with option_context("display.max_rows", None, "display.min_rows", 12):
 506             # max_rows of None -> never truncate
 507             assert ".." not in repr(df)
 508             assert ".." not in df._repr_html_()

 536     def test_to_string_truncate(self):
 537         # GH 9784 - dont truncate when calling DataFrame.to_string
 538         df = pd.DataFrame(
 539             [
 540                 {
 541                     "a": "foo",
 542                     "b": "bar",
 543                     "c": "let's make this a very VERY long line that is longer "
 544                     "than the default 50 character limit",
 545                     "d": 1,
 546                 },
 547                 {"a": "foo", "b": "bar", "c": "stuff", "d": 1},
 548             ]
 549         )
 550         df.set_index(["a", "b", "c"])

 552             "     a    b                                         "
 553             "                                                c  d\n"
 554             "0  foo  bar  let's make this a very VERY long line t"
 555             "hat is longer than the default 50 character limit  1\n"
 556             "1  foo  bar                                         "
 557             "                                            stuff  1"

 565                 "hat is longer than the default 50 character limit  1\n"
 566                 "1  foo  bar                                         "
 567                 "                                            stuff  1"
 568             )

 604     def test_to_string_repr_unicode(self):
 605         buf = StringIO()
 606 
 607         unicode_values = ["\u03c3"] * 10
 608         unicode_values = np.array(unicode_values, dtype=object)
 609         df = DataFrame({"unicode": unicode_values})
 610         df.to_string(col_space=10, buf=buf)
 611 
 612         # it works!
 613         repr(df)
 614 
 615         idx = Index(["abc", "\u03c3a", "aegdvg"])
 616         ser = Series(np.random.randn(len(idx)), idx)
 617         rs = repr(ser).split("\n")
 618         line_len = len(rs[0])
 619         for line in rs[1:]:
 620             try:
 621                 line = line.decode(get_option("display.encoding"))
 622             except AttributeError:
 623                 pass
 624             if not line.startswith("dtype:"):
 625                 assert len(line) == line_len
 626 
 627         # it works even if sys.stdin in None
 628         _stdin = sys.stdin
 629         try:
 630             sys.stdin = None
 631             repr(df)
 632         finally:
 633             sys.stdin = _stdin

 666     def test_to_string_with_formatters(self):
 667         df = DataFrame(
 668             {
 669                 "int": [1, 2, 3],
 670                 "float": [1.0, 2.0, 3.0],
 671                 "object": [(1, 2), True, False],
 672             },
 673             columns=["int", "float", "object"],
 674         )
 675 
 676         formatters = [
 677             ("int", lambda x: f"0x{x:x}"),
 678             ("float", lambda x: f"[{x: 4.1f}]"),
 679             ("object", lambda x: f"-{x!s}-"),
 680         ]
 681         result = df.to_string(formatters=dict(formatters))
 682         result2 = df.to_string(formatters=list(zip(*formatters))[1])
 683         assert result == (
 684             "  int  float    object\n"
 685             "0 0x1 [ 1.0]  -(1, 2)-\n"
 686             "1 0x2 [ 2.0]    -True-\n"
 687             "2 0x3 [ 3.0]   -False-"
 688         )
 689         assert result == result2

1448     def test_to_string(self):
1449 
1450         # big mixed
1451         biggie = DataFrame(
1452             {"A": np.random.randn(200), "B": tm.makeStringIndex(200)},
1453             index=np.arange(200),
1454         )
1455 
1456         biggie.loc[:20, "A"] = np.nan
1457         biggie.loc[:20, "B"] = np.nan
1458         s = biggie.to_string()
1459 
1460         buf = StringIO()
1461         retval = biggie.to_string(buf=buf)
1462         assert retval is None
1463         assert buf.getvalue() == s
1464 
1465         assert isinstance(s, str)
1466 
1467         # print in right order
1468         result = biggie.to_string(
1469             columns=["B", "A"], col_space=17, float_format="%.5f".__mod__
1470         )
1471         lines = result.split("\n")
1472         header = lines[0].strip().split()
1473         joined = "\n".join(re.sub(r"\s+", " ", x).strip() for x in lines[1:])
1474         recons = read_csv(StringIO(joined), names=header, header=None, sep=" ")
1475         tm.assert_series_equal(recons["B"], biggie["B"])
1476         assert recons["A"].count() == biggie["A"].count()
1477         assert (np.abs(recons["A"].dropna() - biggie["A"].dropna()) < 0.1).all()
1478 
1479         # expected = ['B', 'A']
1480         # assert header == expected
1481 
1482         result = biggie.to_string(columns=["A"], col_space=17)
1483         header = result.split("\n")[0].strip().split()
1484         expected = ["A"]
1485         assert header == expected
1486 
1487         biggie.to_string(columns=["B", "A"], formatters={"A": lambda x: f"{x:.1f}"})
1488 
1489         biggie.to_string(columns=["B", "A"], float_format=str)
1490         biggie.to_string(columns=["B", "A"], col_space=12, float_format=str)
1491 
1492         frame = DataFrame(index=np.arange(200))
1493         frame.to_string()

2728     def test_repr_min_rows(self):
2729         s = pd.Series(range(20))
2730 
2731         # default setting no truncation even if above min_rows
2732         assert ".." not in repr(s)
2733 
2734         s = pd.Series(range(61))
2735 
2736         # default of max_rows 60 triggers truncation if above
2737         assert ".." in repr(s)
2738 
2739         with option_context("display.max_rows", 10, "display.min_rows", 4):
2740             # truncated after first two rows
2741             assert ".." in repr(s)
2742             assert "2  " not in repr(s)
2743 
2744         with option_context("display.max_rows", 12, "display.min_rows", None):
2745             # when set to None, follow value of max_rows
2746             assert "5      5" in repr(s)
2747 
2748         with option_context("display.max_rows", 10, "display.min_rows", 12):
2749             # when set value higher as max_rows, use the minimum
